 in group and shared/private" patch that Mel mentioned.<br /><br />In fact, looking at that patch description, it does seem to match this<br />particular load a lot. Quoting from the commit message:<br /><br />  "Running 80 tasks in the same group, or as threads of the same process,<br />   results in the memory getting scanned 80x as fast as it would be if a<br />   single task was using the memory.<br /><br />   This really hurts some workloads"<br /><br />So if 80 threads causes 80x as much scanning, a few thousand threads<br />might indeed be really really bad.<br /><br />So once more unto the breach, dear friends, once more.<br /><br />Please.<br /><br />The patch got applied to -tip as commit b5dd77c8bdad, and can be<br />downloaded here:<br /><br />  <a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/tip/tip.git/commit/?id=b5dd77c8bdada7b6262d0cba02a6ed525bf4e6e1">https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/tip/tip.git/commit/?id=b5dd77c8bdada7b6262d0cba02a6ed525bf4e6e1</a><br /><br />(Hmm. It says it's cc'd to me, but I never noticed that patch simply<br />because it was in a big group of other -tip commits.. Oh well).<br /><br />          Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
